---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
import Math from '../components/Math.astro'
import { sourceFile } from '../data/site'
---

<BaseLayout title="Renormalization">
  <section class="page-intro">
    <div class="site-shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">Renormalization</p>

      <h1>Laurent–log expansions, finite parts, anomalies, and renormalized integrals.</h1>

      <p>
        The renormalization layer provides a reusable interface for
        cutoff-dependent geometric quantities and their finite-part
        regularization.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="site-shell grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Laurent–Log Expansion</h3>

        <Math
          display
          tex="\sum_m a_m\varepsilon^m+L\log\varepsilon+o(1)"
        />

        <p>
          Finite exponent support, logarithmic coefficients, and parity
          conditions are recorded separately from analytic remainder estimates.
        </p>

        <a
          class="source-link"
          href={sourceFile('ConformalCovariantOperators/Ambient/PE/Renormalization/LaurentLogExpansion.lean')}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
        >
          Open LaurentLogExpansion.lean ↗
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Finite Parts and Anomalies</h3>

        <Math display tex="\operatorname{FP}(E)=a_0" />

        <Math display tex="\operatorname{Anom}_{\log}(E)=L" />

        <p>
          The constant Laurent coefficient defines the finite part, while the
          logarithmic coefficient is retained as the anomaly.
        </p>

        <a
          class="source-link"
          href={sourceFile('ConformalCovariantOperators/Ambient/PE/Renormalization/FinitePart.lean')}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
        >
          Open FinitePart.lean ↗
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Renormalized Volume</h3>

        <Math
          display
          tex="\operatorname{RenVol}(X)=\operatorname{FP}(\operatorname{Vol}_\varepsilon(X))"
        />

        <p>
          PE cutoff-volume data is connected to the generic finite-part
          mechanism without claiming that the analytic volume expansion is
          derived in this layer.
        </p>

        <a
          class="source-link"
          href={sourceFile('ConformalCovariantOperators/Ambient/PE/Renormalization/Volume.lean')}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
        >
          Open Volume.lean ↗
        </a>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Renormalized Curvature Integrals</h3>

        <Math
          display
          tex="\operatorname{Ren}\!\int I=\operatorname{FP}\!\left(\int_{r>\varepsilon}I\,dV_{g_+}\right)"
        />

        <p>
          A generic invariant parameter allows later curvature-invariant
          modules to use the same cutoff and finite-part infrastructure.
        </p>

        <a
          class="source-link"
          href={sourceFile('ConformalCovariantOperators/Ambient/PE/Renormalization/CurvatureIntegral.lean')}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noreferrer"
        >
          Open CurvatureIntegral.lean ↗
        </a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section border-top">
    <div class="site-shell">
      <div class="note">
        The current implementation formalizes finite-part extraction and the
        interfaces connecting cutoff data to renormalized quantities. Analytic
        existence, convergence, and asymptotic-expansion proofs remain explicit
        external inputs where required.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>